S3 lifecycle and cost management.

Lifecycle rules move objects between storage classes, and eventually delete them, automatically, based on object age. A rule can be scoped to the whole bucket, to a prefix like logs-slash, to objects with specific tags, or to a size range. Transitions only flow downward the cost ladder: Standard to I-A to Glacier. You cannot use lifecycle to promote an object back to a warmer class, and there's a thirty-day minimum before an object can leave Standard for an I-A tier. The key expiration actions are: expire current versions after N days, which is the basic retention cap; expire non-current versions, which is the lever that makes versioned buckets affordable; delete expired delete markers, which is housekeeping; and abort incomplete multipart uploads, a silent cost that most accounts leak.

Three capabilities sit just outside the core and cut cost or effort. S3 Select runs S-Q-L against a single object, in C-S-V, J-SON, or Parquet, server-side, returning only the matching rows; that's a huge saving when you only need a slice of a big file. S3 Batch Operations runs one action across billions of objects as a managed job, like copy, invoke a Lambda per object, retag, restore, or Batch Replication, driven by an S3 Inventory manifest. And S3 Storage Lens is the org-wide analytics dashboard, with twenty-nine-plus metrics across every account and bucket, plus cost recommendations, like buckets missing a lifecycle rule or leaking incomplete uploads.

Together, these are the cost-control toolkit: lifecycle to tier and expire, Select to read less, and Storage Lens to find the waste.
